abstract = {Publisher Summary
This chapter stresses that Arthur Jensen has amply validated the conjecture that there is a general factor of intelligence, and examines the general factor of intelligence. The major problem confronting intelligence research is the focus on individual differences—both conceptually and methodologically. Therefore, the chapter proposes an alternative componential analysis to analyze performance on test items of the kinds found on intelligence tests through information-processing components rather than psychometric factors. Each component corresponds to one of the constituents underlying general cognitive ability, g. The ultimate goal is to identify all such components underlying the general factor, as well as group and possibly even specific factors. The chapter suggests that underlying the solution of analogies and related problems are three qualitative principles of cognition, which are explained in the chapter. The data from research points out that information-processing techniques can be used to rediscover g.}
